I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data using the default parameters:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll try the network_fetcher again, this time to specify the expected JSON format in the options:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data", 
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now that we've successfully fetched the API data, I'll proceed with the next step to validate and parse the data using the data_processing_parser tool:

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {
    "format": "json",
    "validate": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

I'll attempt to use an alternative API endpoint with the network_fetcher tool:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/v2/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we've successfully fetched the data from the alternative endpoint, I'll proceed with parsing and validating the data using the data_processing_parser tool:

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/v2/data",
  "options": {
    "format": "json",
    "validate": true
  }
}
</tool_call>
